                   <handDesc><handNote>The main part of the manuscript is written by two scribes in a neat, angular Glagolitic script. The second scribe, responsible for fols 74r-158v, is indentified as '<persName role="scr">Michael the priest</persName>' in a colophon on 
                     <ref target="https://digital.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/objects/cacb12d4-a456-45e8-8ca2-2aa325af573d/">fol. 158v</ref> (see above). The second scribe's script has the following characteristic features: 
                     <hi rend="bold">а</hi>, <hi rend="bold">д</hi>, <hi rend="bold">ж</hi>, <hi rend="bold">л</hi>, <hi rend="bold">р</hi> and <hi rend="bold">х</hi> rise above the body-height of the other letters; 
                     <hi rend="bold">б</hi>, <hi rend="bold">г</hi>, <hi rend="bold">з</hi>, <hi rend="bold">к</hi>, <hi rend="bold">н</hi>, <hi rend="bold">х</hi>, <hi rend="bold">ц</hi>, and the vertical stroke in <hi rend="bold">о</hi> and <hi rend="bold">ѹ</hi>, 
                     descend below the base-line; the vertical stroke in <hi rend="bold">щ</hi> extends above the body-height of the other letter-forms and also below the base-line; the vowel <hi rend="bold">о</hi>
                     is ligatured to its consonant and is suspended above it when appropriate. Initials are simple. An  inverted Latin <hi rend="bold">S</hi> in used on fols 6r and 20r; 
                     a Latin <hi rend="bold">P</hi> on fol. 45r; a Latin <hi rend="bold">G</hi> on fols 90r and 92r; and a Latin <hi rend="bold">A</hi> on fol. 96r. The final texts in the manuscript are the work of furhter scribes, 
                     e. g. the Sermon on Death (fol. 158v)  and the ecclesiastical calendar (fols 161r-161v) are each in a different hand</handNote></handDesc>
                  
